data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort()` kills a thread that exceeds a time limit, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` suppresses the re-thrown `ThreadAbortException`. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `ResetAbort()` is a no-op (`SYSLIB0006`).

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injects `ThreadAbortException` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` cancels the re-throw | Obsolete no-op (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks fire | Never fires — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

The fundamental shift: **preemptive → cooperative**. The work itself must check for cancellation.

### Migrated code (recommended)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the CancellationToken for cancellation to work.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

**Usage:**

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    // Check the token at regular intervals in long-running work
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // ... do a unit of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### If you can't modify the work delegate

If callers pass opaque `Func<T>` that you can't change, the work **cannot be forcibly stopped** in .NET 8. You can abandon it (fire-and-forget), but the thread keeps running:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    // WARNING: On timeout the work continues running in the background.
    // This is the best you can do without cooperative cancellation.
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
    {
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }

    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

> ⚠️ This is **not equivalent** to the original — the abandoned work keeps consuming CPU/memory. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Fix |
|---|---|
| `CancellationToken` never checked in work | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at loop checkpoints |
| `Thread.Sleep` inside work ignores token | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| Blocking I/O ignores token | Use async overloads that accept `CancellationToken` |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Always `using var cts = ...` — leaks timers otherwise |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` broadly | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint — design checkpoint frequency for acceptable latency |

### Validation checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort` remain
- ✅ No `SYSLIB0006` warnings
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- ✅ Timeout still throws `TimeoutException` to preserve caller expectations
- ✅ Inner exceptions still propagate via `GetAwaiter().GetResult()`
